---
/**
 * Write detail — "Deleting a Dependency Instead of Duplicating It".
 * Bespoke per-topic body. Structure here: lead → the test → the call → the lesson.
 * Grounded in the homepage summary; deepen the prose with the real specifics anytime.
 */
import WriteLayout from '../../layouts/WriteLayout.astro';
---

<WriteLayout
  slug="deleting-a-dependency"
  title="Deleting a Dependency Instead of Duplicating It"
  dek="A cleanup ticket that ended in removing an SDK entirely."
  description="An engineering-judgment case study: a cleanup ticket that ended in removing an SDK entirely — because a 30-second observability test showed the only feature justifying it was observable nowhere."
>
  <p class="lead" data-reveal>
    The ticket asked for the small thing: tidy up a dependency that two services
    leaned on in slightly different ways. The obvious move was to duplicate the
    glue so each side owned its copy and the coupling went away.
  </p>

  <p data-reveal>
    Before duplicating, I ran a cheaper check first — what does this SDK actually
    earn its place doing? The case for keeping it rested on a single feature. So I
    spent thirty seconds asking the only question that mattered: where does that
    feature show up in production?
  </p>

  <blockquote class="pull" data-reveal>
    The one feature justifying the dependency was observable nowhere.
  </blockquote>

  <p data-reveal>
    No traces, no logs, no metric moved when it ran. The thing the whole dependency
    existed to provide left no evidence it was ever used. Duplicating the glue would
    have carried that dead weight into two places instead of one.
  </p>

  <p class="lesson" data-reveal>
    So the cleanup got smaller and more honest: delete the dependency, not duplicate
    it. The lesson I keep: before you split a thing to make it easier to live with,
    test whether it should live at all. A 30-second observability check beats a
    careful refactor of code that earns nothing.
  </p>
</WriteLayout>

<style>
  .lead {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: clamp(1.3rem, 2.8vw, 1.7rem); line-height: 1.45;
    color: var(--ink); margin-bottom: 1.4rem;
  }
  p {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: clamp(1rem, 2.1vw, 1.12rem); line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--ink-dim);
  }
  p + p { margin-top: 1.2rem; }

  /* Pull-quote — the pivot of the piece, in the gold-rule editorial treatment. */
  .pull {
    margin: clamp(2rem, 5vh, 3rem) 0;
    padding-left: clamp(1rem, 3vw, 1.5rem);
    border-left: 2px solid var(--gold);
    font-family: var(--font-serif); font-style: italic;
    font-size: clamp(1.3rem, 3vw, 1.9rem); line-height: 1.35;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .lesson { color: var(--ink); margin-top: clamp(1.6rem, 4vh, 2.4rem); }
</style>
